### 1.2 Key Design Decisions

| Decision | Rationale |
|----------|-----------|
| **Two separate components** | Data collection independent from analysis; easier to test/debug |
| **Local JSON storage** | No database needed; simple file system; easy to inspect |
| **GitHub Copilot custom agents** | Use built-in Copilot; no extensions to build/maintain |
| **Manual workflow** | Full control; review data before analysis; iterative process |
| **Two-agent approach** | Separation of concerns: analyze → recommend |
| **Markdown output files** | Easy to read, version control, share with team |

### 1.3 Workflow Examples

**Daily Proactive Monitoring:**
```bash
# Cron runs hourly
0 * * * * cd /path/to/ai-monitor && python crawler.py

# In VS Code
# 1. Open workspace with code
# 2. Open Copilot Chat
@analysis-agent analyze the latest New Relic data in data/ folder

# 3. Review generated assessment.md
# 4. If issues found:
@recommend-agent review assessment.md and suggest fixes for the issues
```

**Incident Investigation:**
```bash
# Manually fetch latest data immediately
python crawler.py --app-id prod-web-app --now

# In VS Code Copilot Chat
@analysis-agent analyze data/prod-web-app-latest.json and identify critical issues

# Review assessment.md
# Then get recommendations
@recommend-agent provide specific code fixes for the critical issues in assessment.md
```

**Post-Deployment Check:**
```bash
# After deployment
python crawler.py --app-id prod-web-app

# In VS Code
@analysis-agent compare the latest data with 1 hour ago and show any regressions

# If regressions found
@recommend-agent analyze regressions and suggest rollback or fixes
```

